post_text:
I am pleased to announce that MUSD will be adding an additional location for food service during school closures. Effective, Monday, March 23, 2020, MUSD will provide "Grab and Go" lunch and breakfast each day at both locations listed below. Both locations will provide the same food options, students can pick up food from either location:

MJHS - 11:00 AM to 12:30 PM
Las Juntas Elementary 11:00 AM to 12:00 PM

Food will be provided to all children ages 5-18, regardless of what school they attend in Martinez. Each child will receive a lunch for the day and a breakfast item which can be used the following morning. Students must be present for meal pick up.

Both locations will provide the same food options, students can pick up food from either location:

Las Juntas Elementary 11:00 AM to 12:00 PM

Food will be provided to all children ages 5-18, regardless of what school they attend in Martinez. Each child will receive a lunch for the day and a breakfast item which can be used the following morning. Students must be present for meal pick up.

post_text: The Martinez Unified School District will provide currently enrolled students breakfast and lunch, beginning Tuesday, March 17th, and all weekdays through April 3rd. There will be a pick-up point in front of the Martinez Junior High School gymnasium for both cars and walk-ups. It is required that student(s) be present. Each student will receive a lunch containing an entree, two sides, and milk, along with a cold breakfast for the following day (can be heated). Service will be provided between the hours of 11:00 am and 12:30 pm. If your student has their ID card it would be very helpful, as all meals need to be recorded. We are aware that many students (especially in elementary school and preschool) don’t have their ID card, don’t worry, we can be sure they still get their meal.

Each student will receive a lunch containing an entree, two sides, and milk, along with a cold breakfast for the following day (can be heated). Service will be provided between the hours of 11:00 am and 12:30 pm. If your student has their ID card it would be very helpful, as all meals need to be recorded. We are aware that many students (especially in elementary school and preschool) don’t have their ID card, don’t worry, we can be sure they still get their meal.

post_text: More great news to share! Congratulations to Alhambra High School! Our Bulldogs earned the College Board's AP® Computer Science Female Diversity Award for attaining female student representation in both AP Computer Science A (CSA) and AP Computer Science Principles (CSP) for 2019. Out of 20,000 institutions that offer AP courses, 818 have earned the award. AHS is one of only 36 to be recognized for achieving this important result in both courses. Thanks to Andrea Salas and Chris McKibben for their leadership in this area. I know my 4th-grade daughter would love to try courses like this when she is in high school, maybe your daughter would be interested too!

post_text: Proud to share the announcement that during last night's Board of Education meeting, the MUSD Board of Education passed a resolution to ban the use of glyphosate-based products (products like Roundup). It states, in part, "glyphosate-based product be immediately removed from all District sites, disposed of properly, and banned from all future use from this day forward." Another step toward safer school environments for our students, staff, and community.
text: Proud to share the announcement that during last night's Board of Education meeting, the MUSD Board of Education passed a resolution to ban the use of glyphosate-based products (products like Roundup). It states, in part, "glyphosate-based product be immediately removed from all District sites, disposed of properly, and banned from all future use from this day forward." Another step toward safer school environments for our students, staff, and community.

post_text:
Have you thought about working in our district? We are always hiring great people to work behind the scenes or at the sites. Do you like working directly with children or do you prefer cooking, cleaning, answering phones or doing other types of work that impact our schools? Do you need to be able to drop off and pick up your children from school? Have you considered a job that might allow you to work while your children are in school and also be with them on non-school days when they are home?

We may have something that fits within your interests, talents and availability. We have regular positions and substitute positions.

Jobs are posted regularly on www.edjoin.org

If you have any questions, please contact the Personnel Department at (925)335-5912.

post_text: Huge congratulations to the staff and students of AHS! Alhambra was just awarded the 2018 AP Computer Science Female Diversity Award! The College Board recognized AHS because of the female student representation in AP Computer Science Principles for 2018. Among 18,000 secondary schools worldwide that offer AP courses, Alhambra is one of only 685 that received this important result! Thanks to the teachers who are leading this great work in Computer Science, the administrators supporting the work, and the students taking action to sign up for these courses! Go Bulldogs!

post_text: A great morning at AHS - focused on students and school safety! This week is Say Something week and our student club, SAVE (Students Against Violence Everywhere) hosted a wonderful event. Thanks to Nicole Hockley, co-founder of the Sandy Hook Promise for coming to talk with students. Students also heard from District Attorney, Diana Becton, Assembly Member, Tim Grayson, as well as a video appearance from Congressman Mike Thompson and a letter from Congressman Mark DeSaulnier. I am proud of our students who made the pledge to make a difference and help build stronger safer school communities. Proud of our kids and honored to work for them!

Students also heard from District Attorney, Diana Becton, Assembly Member, Tim Grayson, as well as a video appearance from Congressman Mike Thompson and a letter from Congressman Mark DeSaulnier. I am proud of our students who made the pledge to make a difference and help build stronger safer school communities. Proud of our kids and honored to work for them!
